1. Jackson ‚â† Java Serialization

Serializable is used by Java‚Äôs built-in serialization (e.g., writing objects to disk or sending them over sockets via ObjectOutputStream).

Jackson, on the other hand, uses reflection and introspection to convert objects to/from JSON.
It doesn‚Äôt care about Serializable ‚Äî it looks for:

Public fields
Getters/setters
Or fields annotated / visible by configuration.

‚úÖ 2. When Serializable Might Still Appear
You may still see classes implementing Serializable for reasons unrelated to Jackson, such as:
You want to store objects in HTTP sessions, caches, etc.
You use frameworks that require it (like old-school Java EE or some Spring session setups).
But Jackson doesn‚Äôt require or use it.

üí° 3. Example (without Serializable)
import com.fasterxml.jackson.databind.ObjectMapper;

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception {
        ObjectMapper mapper = new ObjectMapper();

        TestObject obj = new TestObject("Alice", 25);
        String json = mapper.writeValueAsString(obj);
        System.out.println(json);
    }
}

class TestObject {
    private String name;
    private int age;

    public TestObject(String name, int age) {
        this.name = name;
        this.age = age;
    }

    public String getName() { return name; }
    public int getAge() { return age; }
}


‚úÖ Output:

{"name":"Alice","age":25}

No implements Serializable needed ‚Äî it works perfectly.

üß† Summary
Purpose	Needs Serializable?	Example
Jackson JSON serialization	‚ùå No	ObjectMapper.writeValueAsString(obj)
Java native serialization	‚úÖ Yes	ObjectOutputStream.writeObject(obj)
Storing in HTTP session	‚öôÔ∏è Often yes	Framework dependent

So:
‚û°Ô∏è For Jackson ‚Üí Not required.
‚û°Ô∏è Only needed for Java‚Äôs native object serialization mechanisms.

